## Why This Question Is Asked

This question tests knowledge of real-time signal processing on embedded systems, specifically the trade-offs between algorithmic sophistication and computational constraints in audio source separation.

## Key Concepts

**Per-bin ICA vs Joint Diagonalization**: Per-bin ICA processes each frequency bin independently using natural gradient or FastICA, requiring O(K) operations per bin where K is the demixer size. Joint diagonalization (like JADE) jointly optimizes all bins, offering better convergence but O(K²B) complexity—prohibitive for real-time DSP. For 8 microphones and 2 sources, per-bin ICA with 512-1024 FFT bins is feasible within the latency budget.

**Demixer Size Selection**: A 2×2 demixer directly matches the two talkers, minimizing computations (4 complex elements vs 9 for 3×3). The 3×3 option could provide robustness to model order mismatch but adds ~2.25× computational overhead. For moving talkers in a warehouse, the 2×2 is preferred.

**Latency Budget**: With 20 ms frames (320 samples at 16 kHz), a 512-point FFT provides ~16 ms frequency resolution with 50% overlap (8 ms hop). Total pipeline: frame buffer (20 ms) + FFT (0.5 ms) + ICA (2-3 ms) + IFFT (0.5 ms) + output buffer (5 ms) ≈ 28-30 ms.

**Recursive Whitening**: Maintains a running covariance estimate R = λR + (1-λ)xxᵀ where λ∈[0.95,0.99] is the forgetting factor. Lower λ (0.9-0.95) tracks faster but converges noisier; higher λ (0.98-0.99) gives smoother estimates but slower adaptation.

**Diagonal Loading**: Essential for fixed-point stability. Add εI to the whitened covariance matrix where ε = 0.01-0.1 × max(eigenvalues). Prevents division by near-zero values and improves numerical conditioning.

## Code Skeleton

```c
// Fixed-point recursive whitening with forgetting factor
void recursive_whiten(fixed_t *cov_matrix, fixed_t *x_vec, 
                      fixed_t lambda, fixed_t diag_loading) {
    // x_vec: [real, imag] interleaved for current bin
    // cov_matrix: 2x2 complex = 8 real elements

    fixed_t x_real = x_vec[0];
    fixed_t x_imag = x_vec[1];

    // Update covariance: R = lambda * R + (1-lambda) * x * x^H
    for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < 2; j++) {
            fixed_t outer = mul_fixed(x_real, x_real); // simplified
            cov_matrix[i*2+j] = add_fixed(
                mul_fixed(lambda, cov_matrix[i*2+j]),
                mul_fixed(sub_fixed(ONE, lambda), outer)
            );
        }
    }

    // Diagonal loading for stability
    for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
        cov_matrix[i] = add_fixed(cov_matrix[i], diag_loading);
    }
}

// Natural gradient update for 2x2 demixer
void update_demixer(fixed_t W[4], fixed_t x[2], fixed_t mu) {
    // W = W + mu * (I - W*x*x^H*W^H) * W  (natural gradient)
    fixed_t y[2];  // outputs
    fixed_t grad[4];

    // y = W * x (complex multiplication)
    y[0] = sub_fixed(mul_fixed(W[0], x[0]), mul_fixed(W[1], x[1]));
    y[1] = add_fixed(mul_fixed(W[0], x[1]), mul_fixed(W[1], x[0]));

    // Simplified update: W = W + mu * (I - W*W^T) (real approximation)
    for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
        W[i] = add_fixed(W[i], mul_fixed(mu, grad[i]));
    }
}

// Main ICA pipeline (called every frame)
void process_ica_frame(int16_t *mic_input, int16_t *src_output) {
    // 1. FFT (20ms window, 512-point)
    complex_t X[512];
    fft_512(mic_input, X);

    // 2. Per-bin ICA (every 5-10 frames for stability)
    static int frame_count = 0;
    if (frame_count++ % UPDATE_INTERVAL == 0) {
        for (int b = 0; b < NUM_BINS; b++) {
            recursive_whiten(R_xx[b], X[b].val, LAMBDA, DIAG_LOAD);
            update_demixer(W[b], X[b].val, MU);
        }
    }

    // 3. Separate sources
    complex_t Y[2][512];
    for (int b = 0; b < NUM_BINS; b++) {
        matmul_2x2(W[b], X[b], Y[0][b]);
    }

    // 4. IFFT and overlap-add
    ifft_512(Y[0], src_output);
}
```

## Design Rationale

The 2×2 demixer size is optimal because the warehouse scenario has exactly 2 moving talkers, matching the model order precisely. A 3×3 would add unnecessary complexity (125% more multiplications per bin) without benefit unless noise reference channels were explicitly added. The 5-10 frame update cadence prevents the demixer from chasing noise artifacts while still tracking speaker movement—critical for the moving talkers requirement. Diagonal loading is mandatory for 16-bit fixed-point to avoid overflow and maintain numerical stability across the 512+ frequency bins.

