## Key Implementation Details

### Whitening
The forgetting-factor whitening approach maintains an exponential moving average of the input covariance matrix. This enables adaptation to non-stationary noise while stabilizing the demixer convergence. The forgetting factor typically ranges from 0.95 to 0.99 depending on the speed of environmental changes.

### Dynamic Demixer Sizing
The demixer dynamically adjusts between 2–4 sources based on real-time activity detection. This is achieved through eigenvalue analysis of the demixing matrix or energy-based source presence scoring. When speaker movement or new sources are detected, the demixer expands or contracts accordingly.

### Cross-Bin Alignment
Permutation ambiguity is addressed through frequency-bin consistency enforcement. By comparing the time-frequency structures across bins and using the labeled reference window as an anchor, we can reliably track source identity across all frequencies.

### Update Cadence
The system employs a hierarchical update strategy: fast updates (every 10–50ms) for tracking moving speakers and slow updates (every 500ms–2s) for structural adaptation. This balances responsiveness with stability.

### On-Device Evaluation Plan
Ground-truth evaluation uses pre-recorded multi-speaker sessions with known source counts and identities. Metrics include SI-SNR improvement, SDR, and PESQ scores, measured against isolated source references captured during calibration.

